<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-696-160  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 696 160.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Sept 25 1989 n267 p50(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Choosing a local net's foundation. (transmission-system design andchoice of media as crucial elements)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Semilof, Margie.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In setting up private transmission-system architectures,communications managers are recognizing that transmission designand the choice of media are about the most crucial elements.andO;Transmission facilities can be wide area transmission, localcabling or a combination of both, depending on the application.andO;The media choice, that sets the foundation on which the networkwill run, depends on the type of company, application, buildingstructures and cost factors.andP;  Among the types of media availableare copper wire, coaxial cable and optical fiber.andP;  The cost oftransmission media can take up 40 percent of a network's entirecost.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Private NetworksTransmission LinesNetwork ArchitectureNetwork ManagementCoaxial CablesFiber Optics.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>